node.title: West Hollywood hopes to become Amsterdam-like pot-based tourist lure
node.description: The city plans to go green, as in letting the cannabis industry expand and transforming entertainment there in a way similar to the famously popular European weed-tourism focal point Amsterdam.

node.title: Pressure mounts to strip Activision’s chief of his seat on Coca-Cola’s board.
node.description: A union-led investment group plans to ask the beverage maker not to renominate Bobby Kotick as a director, a call that comes after the group called for him to resign from Activision.

node.title: India’s Farmers Call Off Yearlong Protest Against Hated Farm Laws
node.description: Though Prime Minister Modi had unexpectedly conceded to their main demand weeks ago, the farmers had vowed to remain until the formal repeal.

node.title: Boris Johnson and Wife, Carrie Johnson, Announce Birth of Second Child
node.description: The birth comes as the British prime minister faces a political scandal over Covid rules.

node.title: Bogong moth, grey-headed flying fox listed as endangered
node.description: Once found in such overwhelming numbers they even troubled athletes at the Sydney Olympics, the bogong moth is one of a number of Australian species that has now been declared as endangered.

node.title: Australia will 'pay the price' for Winter Olympics boycott, China says
node.description: Australia, the United States, the United Kingdom and Canada will "pay the price" for a diplomatic boycott of the Beijing 2022 Winter Olympic Games, a spokesperson for the Chinese government says.

node.title: More companies paid no tax during COVID-19 pandemic
node.description: The number of Australian public companies that paid no tax in 2019–20 has risen during COVID-19 lockdowns, according to the Australian Taxation Office's (ATO's) latest transparency data.

node.title: Watch Live: Bob Dole lies in state in the U.S. Capitol
node.description: The WWII veteran, senator and GOP presidential candidate died Sunday at age of 98.

node.title: Italy fines Amazon $1.3 billion, saying it hurts other sellers
node.description: Penalty is one of the biggest against the online retailer, which Italian authorities accuse of abusing its dominance.

node.title: Hoping for a Dog Phone? You May Have a Long Wait.
node.description: A scientist in Scotland tested a so-called DogPhone to let her dog make video calls. He did use it, but mostly by mistake.

node.title: Amazon is fined $1.3 billion in Italy over antitrust violations.
node.description: In an investigation into how the e-commerce giant gains an advantage over competitors, regulators said third-party vendors paying for Fulfillment by Amazon received special perks.

node.title: Google Year in Search 2021: The Top Queries of the Past Year Revealed
node.description: Google has revealed the top trending searches from the past year. Here are some of the most interesting findings, and a few surprises as well.

node.title: Video shows Coast Guard pulling body from car above Niagara Falls
node.description: Video shows the rescue swimmer with an axe in his left hand being lowered 80 feet to the submerged car through falling snow.

node.title: Un manual para la fiesta navideña pandémica
node.description: Si el desafío de la temporada de fiestas decembrinas en 2020 era cancelarlo todo, en 2021 la dificultad es cómo volver a la acción.

node.title: Not Home for the Holidays
node.description: Liberated by the loss of tradition over the last two years, some are forging their own celebrations — or skipping them altogether.

node.title: ‘Mr. Saturday Night’ Review: A Producer Who Found His Groove
node.description: If you expect to learn much about Robert Stigwood, this new documentary about the famed manager (of the Bee Gees) and producer (of “Saturday Night Fever”) will leave you frustrated.

node.title: ‘The Unforgivable’ Review: Mirthless in Seattle
node.description: Sandra Bullock plays a woman on parole in this Netflix film adaptation of a British mini-series.

node.title: ‘Last and First Men’ Review: Pondering Posterity
node.description: Tilda Swinton narrates the bleak future of humanity in the only feature directed by the Icelandic composer Johann Johannsson.

node.title: ‘Encounter’ Review: The Scenic Route
node.description: A volatile veteran attempts to rescue his sons from a perceived alien threat in this confused cross between sci-fi thriller and family drama.

node.title: ‘Joy Womack: The White Swan’ Review: When Success Is a Stretch
node.description: This documentary chronicles an American ballet dancer’s efforts to become a star in Russia.

node.title: ‘Agnes’ Review: A Crisis of Faith, and Filmmaking
node.description: In this plodding horror-drama from Mickey Reece, a possessed nun drives one of her sisters to leave their convent.

node.title: ‘Beijing Spring’ Review: The Politics of Aesthetics
node.description: This new documentary chronicles the movement for democratic artistic expression that exploded in the wake of the Cultural Revolution in China.

node.title: ‘National Champions’ Review: A College Football Revolution
node.description: Athletes go on strike seeking health insurance in this drama as a coach tries to forge his legacy.

node.title: ‘The Real Charlie Chaplin’ Review: Not Enough Funny Business
node.description: The documentary attempts to restore a sense of mystery to Chaplin’s life and work, but the filmmakers mostly run through a well-trodden timeline.

node.title: Five Holiday Movies to Stream
node.description: A list of quality holiday movies on streaming services other than Netflix.

node.title: Omicron Seems Mild so Far but People Will Die From It, WHO Expert Maria Van Kerkhove Warns
node.description: WHO COVID technical lead Maria Van Kerkhove has cautioned against referring to Omicron's symptoms as "mild" following some early data on its severity.

node.title: Senators Demand Clarity on U.S. Defense of Taiwan Against China
node.description: Members of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee told key Biden officials on Wednesday that the U.S. needed to clarify its intent to safeguard Taiwan.

node.title: COVID vaccine to be rolled out to children aged five to 11 from early January
node.description: The nationwide rollout of COVID-19 vaccines to Australian children aged between 5 and 11 will begin early next year, the federal government says, but there will be key differences to the rollout for adults.

node.title: Amazon fined $1.3 billion in Italy for using logistics system to gain an unfair edge.
node.description: Regulators said third-party vendors paying for Fulfillment by Amazon received special perks.

node.title: Hong Kong convicts jailed pro-democracy activist of yet another crime
node.description: As China's crackdown on dissent continues, Amnesty International blasts conviction of Jimmy Lai, 2 others, "simply for their involvement in a peaceful, socially distanced vigil."
